<paragraph blockId="18.[813,1420,1138,1430]" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,974,1138,1162]" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">Identification.</emphasis>
This species is characterized by having short stems and internodes, intact, persistent and cucculate cataphylls, petioles usually ribbed, pendent inflo- rescences, and lilac, tapered and slender spadices. In the field, this species can be confused with 
<taxonomicName authority="Engl. ex K. Krause" authorityName="K. Krause" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Anthurium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="18" pageNumber="669" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ramonense">
<emphasis box="[1267,1420,1272,1296]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">A. ramonense</emphasis>
Engl. ex K. Krause
</taxonomicName>
and with juvenile individuals of 
<taxonomicName authority="Guillaumin" authorityName="Guillaumin" class="Liliopsida" family="Araceae" genus="Anthurium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Alismatales" pageId="18" pageNumber="669" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="michelii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="669">A. michelii</emphasis>
Guillaumin
</taxonomicName>
, but both differs because they lack cucculate cataphylls (see the additional differences in the notes on both species).
</paragraph>
